english:
  title: A Letter Left for the Mongolian Envoy Regarding Japan
  author: Lee Chang-yong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Japan lies ten thousand li across the sea. Though it has occasionally maintained contact with the Middle Kingdom, it has never regularly paid tribute year after year. Thus the Middle Kingdom paid it little heed—welcoming it when it came, severing ties when it departed, deeming its acquisition worthless to the royal transformation and its abandonment no loss to imperial dignity.

    Now that a sage and brilliant ruler sits upon the throne, with the sun and moon illuminating all beneath heaven, even the most remote lands have become subjects. Could such an ignorant small people dare resist? Yet who can ignore the venom of the bee and scorpion? To send an official letter seems likewise unwise.

    During the Sui, when Emperor Wen ruled, their envoy wrote: "From the Son of Heaven where the sun rises, to the Son of Heaven where the sun sets." Such arrogance, such disrespect for proper names and ranks! How can we know if such pride does not persist even now? Once an official letter enters their hands, should they return haughty words or disrespectful language, we face a dilemma: to reject them brings dishonor to the great court; to accept brings us to waters and winds too treacherous for the imperial armies.

    I, your humble minister, well know the magnanimous policies of the great court, and do not necessarily seek such entanglement. I merely undertook this experiment at another's suggestion. Yet given such circumstances, it seems better not to send the official seal at all.

    Have they not heard of the great court's boundless virtue and merit? If they have heard, they should come to pay homage. That they do not must mean they rely only upon the sea's distance. Then let us wait and observe their actions in time. Should they come, we praise their submission. Should they not, we set them aside and let them live in their isolated realm, unremembered—this is the supreme virtue of the sage, whose benevolence covers all without partiality.

    Should I again stand before your majesty and receive your favor directly, then though I remain in this distant corner, with the loyalty of a faithful servant, I shall strive with all my heart to repay even a fraction of your kindness.
  footnotes:
    - '職貢 (direct tribute): The formal system of tributary relations where foreign states periodically sent envoys bearing gifts to the Chinese court.'
    - The reference to Sui Emperor Wen and Japan's arrogant greeting reflects a historical incident where Japanese envoys used language suggesting equality rather than subordination to Chinese authority.
    - '天覆無私 (heaven''s impartial covering): A classical phrase describing the virtue of allowing all things to flourish naturally without interference, a principle of sage rulership.'
